    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also saw a note about how blockages can mess it up. like if bugs get stuck in there or something. does that happen often? and what kind of blockages are we talking about?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, blockages in the pitot tube can indeed occur and are a concern for pilots. Common blockages include insects, debris, dirt, or even ice, which can obstruct the tube's opening. This obstruction prevents air from flowing freely into the tube, leading to inaccurate airspeed readings. Insect blockages are the most frequent, but other blockages can also cause similar problems. Regular inspections and maintenance are crucial to ensure the pitot tube remains clear and functional. Pilots are trained to recognize the signs of a blockage, such as a sudden loss of airspeed indication, and take appropriate action, which may include reducing speed and landing at the nearest safe location to address the issue.",
      "source": "target",
