      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, there are several other factors besides dirt and ice that can compromise the pitot tube's functionality. For instance, hail or heavy rain can cause water to build up in the tube, leading to inaccurate readings. Extreme turbulence can also result in damage or dislodgement of the pitot tube from its mounting. Moreover, bird strikes are another potential hazard that can damage the pitot tube or cause blockages. Additionally, the pitot tube must be shielded from the sun to prevent overheating, which can affect its performance. Regular maintenance and pre-flight checks are crucial to identify and address any issues that might compromise the pitot tube's accuracy. Pilots are trained to handle these situations and take necessary precautions to ensure the aircraft's safety.",
